# AI Development Rules — Trellis HOA Platform

## Code Changes
- Aim for the smallest possible code change that achieves the goal
- Always check existing code before writing new code — avoid duplicating utilities, types, or patterns
- Read the full file before editing — understand context before changing
- When modifying a file, preserve existing patterns and conventions in that file
- If a change requires touching more than 5 files, stop and discuss the approach first

## Code Quality
- Never disable ESLint rules with inline comments — fix the code instead
- Never use `@ts-ignore` or `@ts-expect-error` — fix the types
- Never commit console.log — use the Pino structured logger
- Never hardcode secrets, API keys, or environment-specific values — use env vars
- Prefer early returns over deeply nested conditionals
- Keep functions under 40 lines — extract helpers if longer

## Dependencies
- Check if an existing package already solves the problem before adding new ones
- Prefer packages already in the monorepo's dependency tree
- For new packages: check weekly downloads, last publish date, TypeScript support, and bundle size
- Never add packages that duplicate existing functionality

## Testing
- Write tests for business logic, especially state machine transitions and financial calculations
- Test RLS isolation explicitly — verify cross-tenant data leakage is impossible
- Use meaningful test names that describe the scenario and expected outcome
- Mock external services (Stripe, Clerk, AWS) — never call real APIs in tests

## Security
- NEVER log PII (email, phone, SSN, financial account numbers)
- NEVER expose internal error details to API responses
- ALWAYS validate and sanitize user input via Zod before use
- ALWAYS use parameterized queries — never string-concatenate SQL
- ALWAYS set tenant context before database queries — RLS prevents accidental leaks

## HOA Domain Knowledge
- A "tenant" in our system is an HOA (the Clerk Organization)
- A "member" is a homeowner or resident — not a platform user
- A single user can belong to multiple HOAs with different roles
- Violations follow a strict state machine — never skip states without explicit board override
- Financial operations require separation of duties (maker ≠ checker)
- Multi-state compliance: check the compliance_profiles table before applying any state-specific rule
- Washington State (RCW 64.38 / WUCIOA RCW 64.90) is the primary compliance baseline

## Git
- Atomic commits with descriptive messages: `feat(violations): add courtesy notice generation`
- Prefixes: feat, fix, refactor, docs, test, chore, perf
- Include the domain scope: (violations), (finance), (auth), (mobile), (infra)
- One logical change per commit — don't mix unrelated changes
